Incident.Summary: Attempted burglary and malicious destruction of property.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Crime:
Second degree burglary
Malicious Destruction of Property
Scene Processing:
Digital photographs were taken of the scene and uploaded to Veripic.
Attachments:
None
Victim:
Troy Snyder (DOB: 11/14/1972)
34430 Old Ocean City Road Unit D, Pittsville, Wicomico County, Maryland 21850
Phone Number: (717) 577-6071 or (717) 577-6069
Interviewed:
Aftab Ahmed Khan Burki (DOB: 02/26/1962)
317 Brookview Drive, Salisbury, Wicomico County, Maryland 21804
Phone Number: (443) 239-7868
Suspect/ Offender:
Information not known at this time.
Narrative:
On 02/11/2023 at approximately 0729 hours I, TFC Honsinger, was dispatched to the Pittsville Mart located at 34430 Old Ocean City Road, Pittsville, Wicomico County, Maryland 21850 for a report of a burglary after the fact.
When I arrived on scene, I observed one of the glass doors to the Pittsville Mart was broken after being struck by a hard object multiple times. I entered into the business and made contact with the complainant, Aftab Ahmed Khan Burki (hereinafter referred to as “Aftab”), and took a verbal statement. Aftab stated he opened the store at 0700 hours and when he arrived he did not notice the door had been broken because he normally opened that door at a later time. Aftab stated a customer entered into the business and advised him of the broken door. Aftab stated he contacted his boss in reference to the door being broken and he was advised to contact the police. Aftab stated they only rent space in the building for the store, and the owner of the building is named Tony Snyder (hereinafter referred to as “Tony”). I asked Aftab if he knew who would have possibly done this and he stated they have been having problems with a black male that has been stealing stuff from the store. Aftab stated he does not know the name of the male but described him as being a black male approximately 601, weighing 160-170 pounds with braids that are shoulder length. Aftab stated he believed the black male had a girlfriend that lived in the Talbot Apartments down the street. I asked Aftab about the security cameras that I observed inside the store as well as outside, and he stated the inside ones do not work, but the outside ones do but are controlled by Tony.
After clearing the scene, I attempted to contact Tony in reference to the attempted burglary and malicious destruction of property. Upon making contact, Tony advised he did have access to the cameras and would check to see if he was able to see the crime occur.
On 02/16/2023 Tony contacted me and sent me multiple images of a what appears to be an unknown black male dressed entirely in black in front of the store at 0610 hours on 02/11/2023. The suspect arrived on scene in a light colored 2006-2012 Ford Fusion bearing unknown Delaware registration. In some of the photographs the unknown black male can be seen throwing what looks to be a rock against the glass door.  I contacted Chief Harris of the Pittsville Police Department to see if he had any dealings with an individual that drives a similar car or has been around the Talbot Apartments and he stated he did not. Chief Harris stated he would contact the manager of the apartment complex and would advise if he was able to find anything.
I request this case remain open pending further investigation.
On 03/30/2023 I contacted ESIC in reference to sending out a bulletin in reference to this case to see if anyone could give any additional information.

On 04/24/2023 I made contact with media relations of the Maryland State Police in reference to a press release being issued for the area for anyone knowing any information on the unknown suspect or the suspect vehicle. 
    I have also authored a Google Geo Fence warrant which will be served on Google once it has been signed by a judge.

    I request this case remain open and additional supplements to follow.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Interview and Confession of Joshua Johnson
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Focus of supplemental report:

Interview and confession of Joshua David Johnson

Attachments: 

1. Advice of Miranda Rights.
2. Application for Statement of Charges.

Evidence: 

One (1) recorded interview of Joshua David Johnson, stored in the property room of the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack. 

Suspect/ Offender:

Joshua David Johnson (DOB: 01/06/2003) B/M
Address:7409 Gumboro Road, Pittsville, Wicomico County, Maryland 21850.
Phone Number: None

Narrative: 

    During my investigation into the malicious destruction of property and attempted burglary of the Pittsville Mart that took place on February 11, 2023, the complainant Aftab Ahmed Khan Burki (hereinafter referred to as “Aftab”) stated they had been having issues with one of their customers.  Aftab stated he did not know the name of the subject but described him as a black male, approximately 601, weighing 160-170 pounds, and has shoulder length braids. Aftab stated he believed the subject currently lived in the Talbot Apartments. While conducting my investigation, an armed robbery occurred in Willards, Maryland on February 28, 2023 and the subject that conducted the armed robbery matched the description of the possible suspect from my case. 
After CPL Hager of the Maryland State Police had concluded his interview with Johnson I began my portion of the interview. 
    On May 23, 2023 at approximately 1103 hours, I, TFC Honsinger of the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack conducted an interview of Joshua David Johnson while conducting an extradition from SCI to the Wicomico County Detention Center. The interview was recorded and below is a synopsis of the interview and not a transcript therefore paraphrasing may be used:
    •    Questioning begins at the 25:10 mark of the recording. 
    •     Johnson stated he was living in Pittsville, Maryland during the time of the incident.
    •    Johnson stated he was familiar with the Pittsville Mart.
    •    Johnson stated he did not remember where he was on February 11, 2023. 
    •    Johnson stated he saw the door of the Pittsville Mart.
    •    Johnson stated it was not him in the surveillance footage. 
    •    Johnson stated he and the store had issues. 
    •    Johnson stated one store owner gave him a vape and the other wanted to make him pay $25 for it.
    •    Johnson then stated it was him that broke the window to the door because he was mad about the vape incident.
    •    Johnson stated he was “drunk as shit” and went back to the store in friend’s car by himself.
    •    Johnson stated he went to his “baby mama’s” house after breaking the window of the door. 
    •    Johnson stated the store owner told his girlfriend to have him come to the store to talk or else it would go bad for him.  
    •    Johnson stated he was “making them pay for it”
    Based on the above interview and confession of Johnson, I authored an Application for Charges and sent it to the Wicomico County Commissioners Office on May 24, 2023.
    The victim has been made aware of the case status and advised the cost to repair the door was approximately $450. I request the case remain open pending the issuance of a warrant for his arrest. 
    All events occurred in Wicomico County, Maryland.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeTitle: Google Geo-Fence Stage 3 Results, and case closure.
IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Focus of Supplemental Report:

Results of Stage 3 Data from Google, and case closure.

Attachments:

1. Stage 3 Geo-Fence Warrant.
2. Google Response Letter for Stage 3 Data. 

Narrative:

On June 10, 2023 I, TFC Honsinger #6841, of the Maryland State Police Salisbury Barrack received the response from Google in reference to the Stage 3 Geo-Fence warrant that was served on June 29, 2023 at 1413 hours (2:13 pm).

After reviewing the results from the Stage 3 Geo-Fence Warrant, neither of the phones came back to Joshua Johnson.

I request this case be closed, due to arrest of Joshua Johnson.

Case closed.
